{{Jainism}} '''Dravida Sangha''' was established in 470&nbsp;AD by a [[Tamil Jain|Jain]] monk named Vajranandi in the city of [[Madurai]] in present-day [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is considered to be the forerunner of the legendary [[Tamil Sangam]]s of the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] lore. Madurai at that time was under the sway of the [[Kalabhra]] rule.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Takanobu|title=Tamil Love Poetry and Poetics|pages=232}}</ref> Dravida Sangha was also mentioned by other Jaina literature for alleged laxity of conduct in respect to bathing and eating prescribed food. Furthermore, it was alleged that members of the Sangha also abandoned Jaina religious requirement of wandering mendicancy and adopted settled life such as trading and farming.<ref>{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Narendra|title=Encyclopaedia of Jainism|pages=2891}}</ref> According to Prof. George Hart, who holds the endowed Chair in Tamil Studies by University of California, Berkeley, and has written that the legend of Tamil Sangam (literary assembly) was based on the Jain assembly (Sangham) at Madurai: :"There was a permanent Jaina assembly called a Sa(n)gha established about 604 AD in Maturai.It seems likely that this assembly was the model upon which tradition fabricated the [[Tamil Sangams|cangkam]] legend."<ref>{{cite book|last=Hart|first=George|title=The Milieu of the Ancient Tamil Poems|url=http://tamil.berkeley.edu/html/chapter_1.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/19970709071128/http://tamil.berkeley.edu/html/chapter_1.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=1997-07-09|publisher=University of California, Berkeley}}</ref>
==History== Dravida Sangha was established by Vajranandi in 470 CE.<ref>{{citation |title=Jainism - Its relevance to psychiatric practice; with special reference to the practice of Sallekhana |pmc=5270277 }}</ref>
