[[File:St. Peter Claver church and rectory, Belize.jpg|thumb|St. Peter Claver church and rectory in Punta Gorda, Belize|450px|right]] '''St. Peter Claver Catholic parish''' is located in [[Punta Gorda, Belize|Punta Gorda]], [[Toledo District]], [[Belize]]. ==History== {{Main|History of Belize#Emigration of the Garifuna}} The [[Garifuna people|Garifuna]] arrived in Punta Gorda from the coast of [[Honduras]] in the late 1700s. They had [[Catholic church|Catholic]] roots from their ancestry in [[Dominica]]. In 1862 the first Catholic church among the Garifuna of [[British Honduras]]/Belize was built in Punta Gorda by [[Belgians|Belgian]] [[Jesuit]] Fr. John Genon. From Punta Gorda he served the missions along the coast from Redcliff (Barranco) to [[Stann Creek Town]].<ref>Hopkins, F. (October 1918). The Catholic Church in British Honduras (1851-1918). ''Catholic Historical Review'', Vol. 4: 1-11, 304-314.[https://www.jstor.org/stable/25011583 ''CHR'']</ref> [[File: SarstoonKeckchiVillage.jpg|thumb|left]] After Genon’s death in 1878, Punta Gorda became a [[Holy Redeemer Catholic Parish, Belize City|mission]] visited every other month. In 1883 [[Q'eqchi' people|Q'eqchi']] [[Maya peoples|Maya]] from [[Cobán]], Alta Verapaz, Guatemala, settled in Crique Sarco and Dolores near Punta Gorda. A count of the population in the Toledo District in the 1890s reported around 3700 of whom 3249 were Catholic. School populations included Punta Gorda 100, Barranco 50, [[Monkey River Town]] 40, Sarstoon 90, and [[San Antonio, Toledo|San Antonio]] 120.<ref name=Woods>Woods, Charles M. Sr., et al. ''Years of Grace: The History of Roman Catholic Evangelization in Belize: 1524-2014.'' (Belize: Roman Catholic Diocese of Belize City-Belmopan, 2015).</ref>{{rp|143}}
Many of the Q'eqchi' from Coban worked as laborers on the German-owned Cramer Estates in Temash and [[Sarstoon Temash Institute for Indigenous Management|Sarstoon]] (at left). With World War I the Cramers were forced to close but most Maya remained in the Sarstoon, Temash, and [[Moho River]] areas.<ref>Burns, Sir Alan. ''Colonial Civil Servant'' (Allen & Unwin, 1949).</ref> Jesuit Fr. Herman J. Tenk was pastor of Punta Gorda and this large mission area from 1913 to 1938. To him is attributed the tradition of Garifuna [[History of Roman Catholicism in Belize#Schools|teachers]] in the schools, as he fostered their education and employment.<ref>Arana, F.B. ''The Garifuna teachers: Their contribution to education in Belize,'' 2002, chapter 1.</ref> [[File: NazarethConvent.jpg|thumb|right]]
In 1931 the [[Vincent Pallotti|Pallottine]] sisters built Nazareth, their Belizean [[novitiate]] (pictured at right), at Fairview, four miles northwest of Punta Gorda. They have been active in the Maya villages of Toledo District and have admitted 72 Belizeans into their numbers.
In 1942 Jesuit Fr. [[Marion M. Ganey]] became pastor in Punta Gorda and in 1943 established St. Peter Claver Credit Union, the first of many [[credit union]]s and [[cooperative]]s he would help initiate throughout Belize and later in the [[Fiji]] Islands and South Pacific.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Wallace, F.|title =The Caribs Cooperate|journal =Jesuit Missions | location =Jesuit Archives: Central United States. St. Louis| pages = 9 | date =April 1944}}</ref> In 1961 a secondary school was opened at St. Peter Claver<ref name=Woods/>{{rp|256}} but had to close in around 1980. In 1970 the present church was built. Today It features both Garifuna and Q’eqchi’ choirs.<ref name=Woods/>{{rp|272}}
The parish remains the hub serving 30 Maya [[San Antonio, Toledo|mission stations]], each with its own Catholic-run, government-subsidized grade school. In 2015 St. Peter Claver along with [[St. Martin de Porres Church, Belize City|St. Martin de Porres]] in Belize City were the two parishes in Belize still pastored by members of the [[History of Roman Catholicism in Belize#Jesuits|Society of Jesus]] (Jesuits).<ref>{{cite web| title =Belize| url =http://www.jesuit.org/Assets/Publications/File/JBSummer2013.pdf|page=10|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref>
